    "translations": {
      "en": {
        "summary": "Imam al-Hasan al-Mujtaba (peace be upon him) was asked to define intellect ('aql). He gave a profound two-part answer: true intellect is the ability to swallow one's grief (emotional self-control) and to deal diplomatically with one's enemies (strategic restraint). This was narrated by Abu Sa'id Aqisa, a companion of the Imam, reflecting the practical wisdom the second Imam was known for during the politically turbulent period following the end of his caliphate.",
        "key_terms": {
          "العقل": "Intellect, reason — a core concept in Islamic philosophy denoting the faculty of rational discernment",
          "التجرع": "Swallowing, suppressing — here refers to enduring grief without outward expression",
          "الغصة": "Grief, anguish, a lump in the throat — intense emotional pain",
          "مداهنة": "Gentle dealing, diplomacy, tactful treatment — managing relations with enemies wisely"
        },
        "seo_question": "What did Imam al-Hasan say about the definition of intellect?"
      },
